# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: an-apology-to-elephants
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/100-foot-wave] The third season premiered on May 1, 2025.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/100-foot-wave] McNamara's career as a big-wave surfer is chronicled.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/100-foot-wave] The series focuses on his time in Nazaré, where he hopes to find and conquer a 100-foot wave.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/100-foot-wave] He works alongside Nazaré locals to transform the town into a surfing destination known for its immense waves.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/100-foot-wave] Other big-wave surfers are also profiled.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/100-foot-wave] Smith was approached by Joe Lewis to direct a documentary feature film about McNamara.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/100-foot-wave] However, when the first cut of the film turned out to be six hours long, Smith felt it would be better suited as a docuseries.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/100-foot-wave] In February 2021, it was announced that a 6-episode documentary series would be produced by Topic Studios and distributed by HBO.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/12th-delaware] One of the interviewees was president of the Pregnancy Care Centre, Father Thomas J.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/12th-delaware] In January 2011, Euteneuer issued a statement disclosing that he had "violat[ed] the boundaries of chastity with an adult female ...
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/12th-delaware] I take full responsibility for my own poor judgment, my weakness and my sinful conduct that resulted from it". and then in June 2012, it was reported that a woman had filed a lawsuit accusing Euteneuer of sexual abuse during what were supposed to be exorcisms.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] The film premiered under its original title *3 1/2 Minutes* at the Sundance Film Festival on January 24, 2015, later winning the Special Jury Prize for Social Impact.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] The film was then bought by HBO Documentary Films, and premiered on HBO on November 23, 2015.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] On December 1, it was one of 15 films shortlisted for the Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature for the 2016 89th Academy Awards.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] The film takes a look at the shooting of Jordan Davis, an African-American teenager who was shot by Michael Dunn on November 23, 2012, at a gas station in Jacksonville, Florida.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] The shooting was sparked by an argument between Dunn and Davis over loud rap music.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] Dunn would later claim in court that he believed that Davis possessed a shotgun and was going to harm him.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] In the film Silver examines the shooting as well as the subsequent trial, media coverage and protests that resulted from the shooting, especially those stemming from the Black Lives Matter movement.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] The film's title refers to the time between when Dunn pulled into the parking spot next to the vehicle Davis was in (seen as 7:30-7:33 PM), and how many bullets were fired (Approximately 10, from Dunn's Taurus PT 99 AF).
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] Plans to create the documentary began when producer Minette Nelson read a 2013 *Rolling Stone* article about the case and Florida's stand-your-ground laws.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] She contacted Silver and asked him to serve as the film's director.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] Through family lawyer John Michael Phillips, Nelson and Silver met Jordan's parents Ron Davis and Lucy McBath.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] Filming took place in Jacksonville, Florida, over a nine-month period in 2013, primarily using a Canon C100.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] Silver and his crew gained permission to film the Dunn trial, but only if they did not film the jury, as this could have resulted in a mistrial.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] They agreed, and filmed the trial from the back of the courtroom.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] The film premiered in the US Documentary Competition at Sundance in 2015.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] After screenings, the film was bought by HBO, to be aired in the late fall of 2015.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] The official trailer for the film was released on YouTube on August 25, 2015, and the film aired on HBO on November 23, 2015, at 9 PM.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] It is currently available for viewing on Google Play.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] Rotten Tomatoes gave the film a 100% rating based on 50 reviews, with an average rating of 7.7/10.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] Matt Zoller Seitz of *RogerEbert.com* gave the film 3 out of 4 stars, saying "The movie's meditative quality makes you feel for everyone involved in this tragedy—even Dunn, who seems very much a prisoner of fear and anger.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] It reminds us of what is broken in our country.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/2-minutes-10-bullets] On December 1, the film was selected as one of 15 shortlisted for the Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] The events inspired the 1964 song "Birmingham Sunday" by Richard and Mimi Fariña, which was used in the opening sequence of the film, as sung by Joan Baez, Mimi's sister.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] They also inspired the 1963 tune "Alabama" by John Coltrane, which is also included in the soundtrack.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] In 2017, the film was selected for preservation in the United States National Film Registry by the Library of Congress as being "culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant".
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] A local chapter of the Ku Klux Klan placed bombs at the 16th Street Baptist Church and set them off as Sunday services prepared to commence on the morning of September 15, 1963.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Four young girls, ranging in age from 11 to 14, were killed in the explosion, which also caused anywhere between 14 and 22 additional injuries.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] The deaths provoked national outrage, and, the following summer, the United States Congress passed the Civil Rights Act of 1964, which was signed by President Lyndon B.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] The bombing is marked in history as a critical and pivotal moment in the Civil Rights Movement.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] The film covered the events in Birmingham, Alabama, in 1963 related to civil rights demonstrations and the movement to end racial discrimination in local stores and facilities.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Martin Luther King Jr. arrived in the town to help with their strategy and to speak at the funeral of the four young girls.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] People of the community met at the 16th Street Baptist Church while organizing their events.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] The demonstrations were covered by national media, and the use by police of police dogs and pressured water from hoses on young people shocked the nation.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] The large number of demonstrators who were arrested resulted in local jails filling capacity.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] The film ends with the trial and conviction in 1977 of Robert Edward Chambliss, also known as Dynamite Bob, as the main person responsible for the bombing, though he is said to have been only one of four Klan members involved.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] The film also references black churches being set on fire in Birmingham in 1993, giving the impression that, while progress has been made, there are some things that still have not changed.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Lee uses interviews with family and friends of the girls, government officials, and civil rights activists, as well as home movies and archival footage, to not only tell the story of the four girls' lives but also to provide a greater historical and political context of the times.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Lee first became interested in making a film about the Birmingham bombing in 1983, when he was a student at New York University.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] After reading a *New York Times Magazine* article about the incident, he was moved to write to Chris McNair, the father of Denise, one of the victims, to ask for permission to tell her story on film.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] McNair turned down the young, aspiring filmmaker.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] "I was entering my first semester at N.Y.U.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] So my skills as a filmmaker were nonexistent, and at that time, Chris McNair was still hesitant to talk about it," Lee said in a 1997 interview with Industry Central's The Director's Chair.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] According to McNair, he changed his mind about supporting Lee's film idea due to learning about the depth and precision of Lee's research.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] McNair said, "[I]t's very important that this be done accurately and correctly.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] In all his research, he [Lee] showed that he was objective and seeking a broad section of opinion.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] At first, Lee had intended to create a dramatic reproduction of the incident, but eventually, he decided that would not be the best approach, and the project became a documentary.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Once he secured funding, he went to Birmingham with a small skeleton film crew, as he wanted the families to be as comfortable as possible during the interviews.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Sam Pollard served as a producer and the editor and Ellen Kuras was the director of photography of the film.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Lee had developed a relationship with Kuras while working on an HBO project called *Subway Stories*, which was an anthology of short films compiled by Jonathan Demme (though Lee's film did not make the final cut due, in part, to conflict between him and Demme).
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Kuras said of her desire to shoot *4 Little Girls*, "I was really interested because my background is in political documentaries ...
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] I always felt that one of the reasons that I had got into filmmaking was that I wanted to use my craft to be able to say something about the human condition, however I could, in my own humble way.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Lee's partnership with Sam Pollard had begun on *Mo' Better Blues* when Pollard was recommended to replace Barry Alexander Brown, who was unavailable because he was directing his own film, as editor.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Pollard originally refused the overture because he was busy working on his segments of *Eyes on the Prize*, but ultimately, he accepted, and he has since become one of Lee's most frequent collaborators.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Their first few films together were fiction, but Pollard's background was in documentary, and he was key to guiding the structure of *4 Little Girls*.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] The film was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] On Rotten Tomatoes, it holds an approval rating of 100% based on 25 reviews, with an average rating of 8.42/10.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Metacritic, which uses a weighted average, assigned the film a score of 88 out of 100, based on 16 critics, indicating "universal acclaim".
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] It was initially planned for the film to first be seen by the public when it was aired on HBO, but, after seeing the final product, the production team decided it was important to release the film in theaters before running it on television.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] Accordingly, *4 Little Girls* opened in American theaters on July 9, 1997, and closed on October 2, 1997.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] It grossed $130,146 from a total of four theaters.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] In its opening weekend, it earned $13,528 from a single theater, which was 10.4% of its total gross.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/4-little-girls] It cost approximately $1 million to make, funded by HBO.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/537-votes] The 2000 United States presidential election came down to the state of Florida, in which the margin between Democratic candidate Al Gore and Republican candidate George W.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/537-votes] The election was left un-decided during a controversial series of recounts in Florida, which after being stopped by the Supreme Court of the United States in the case *Bush v.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/537-votes] Gore*, eventually resulted in Bush winning with a margin of 537 votes in the state.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/537-votes] On Rotten Tomatoes it has a 100% approval rating based on reviews from 8 critics, with an average rating of 7.40/10.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/537-votes] Writing for CNN, Brian Lowry notes that the film was released shortly before the 2020 United States presidential election, where similar concerns existed.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] Premiered in full in 2016, the musical uses mainly pre-existing songs popular throughout the history of the United States to examine and reframe American history through the experiences of marginalized communities.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] The complete production is performed over eight acts, with each act representing three decades of U.S. history.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] Taylor Mac, music director Matt Ray, costume designer Machine Dazzle, and co-director Niegel Smith developed the show over five years, holding workshops and performing abridged versions at festivals and small venues.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] The show was workshopped as part of the Sundance Institute's 2015 Theatre Lab.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] Many productions of the show are abridged versions, with the songs and subject matter confined to specific decades or themes.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] At different touring sites, local performers and artists participate, and the show is modified to incorporate local history and songs from the region.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] Since the premiere performance, the 24-hour production has been staged several times, though broken up into four chapters of six hours each, spread over several days.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] The first of these stagings took place at the Curran Theatre in San Francisco, between September 15 and 24, 2017.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] The Melbourne International Arts Festival hosted the production, playing the four chapters between October 11 and 20, 2017.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] Also during the festival, Taylor Mac performed *The Inauguration* on October 5, an abbreviated version of the show that lasted from 90 minutes to two hours, as well as *The Wrap* on October 22, also featuring songs from the show.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] From March 15 to 24, 2018, the four-chapter production played at the Theater at the Ace Hotel in Los Angeles, presented by the UCLA Center for the Performing Arts (CAP UCLA).
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] The first act only debuted in London at the Barbican Centre as part of the London International Festival of Theatre, being performed on June 28, 29, and 30, 2019.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] In September 2019, abridged versions were performed at four tour stops in the United States, as well as five performances of Mac's *Holiday Sauce* show in December.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] From October 10 to 20, 2019, the four-chapter show played as part of The Berliner Festspiele's Immersion program series.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] On June 14, 2023, the concert film of the same name premiered at Tribeca Festival.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] Directed by Academy Award winners Rob Epstein and Jeffrey Friedman, the film covers the 2016 St.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-24-decade-history-of-popular-music] On June 27, the film aired on HBO and began streaming on Max.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] Narrator Lily Tomlin campaigned on the subject for several years, in the course of which she met Pat Derby.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] Later, she suggested that HBO make a movie about elephant captivity.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] HBO began work on the documentary in 2011.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] It was later joined by PETA, which offered pictures and video footage, including photos from a whistleblower depicting elephant training at the Ringling Bros circus.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] The documentary begins by showing the transfer of elephants from a train; the narrator states that "the elephants need our help".
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] It proceeds with Joyce Poole, an elephant biologist, discussing some of the characteristics of an elephant, including mirror recognition capability.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] Cynthia Moss and Katy Payne explain some of the habits of elephants.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] While discussing anthropomorphism of elephants, Indian scientist Raman Sukumar states that elephants have a love–hate relationship with human society.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] The documentary then describes elephant capture for public display in circuses and zoos.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] After describing the role of elephants in the environment, the documentary depicts some of the training techniques at circuses using bullhooks.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] It then shows an "elephant healing area" created in Northern California by Ed Stewart and Pat Derby, founders of Performing Animal Welfare Society.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] Derby tells the reunion story of Wanda, an elephant from Detroit Zoo, and Gypsy, from one of the circuses from Illinois, who were together in a circus in 1980 and bought together again in 2005.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] It describes various incidents of elephant communication and their emotional bonding; and it relates the story of Topsy from Luna Park, Coney Island, and her electrocution on January 4, 1903.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] The documentary depicts new bullhook-free techniques implemented at Oakland Zoo for elephants; it ends by raising an alarm against the ivory trade, stating that the current elephant killing rate would lead to extinction of the species in ten years.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] The documentary received generally positive feedback on release.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] The *Variety magazine* in its review noted that "*An Apology to Elephants*, in its best moments, is hard to forget" and is "an effective calling card for the animal-rights agenda".
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] Sheri Linden reviewed the documentary for *The Hollywood Reporter* and mentioned that it is "a succinct, graceful argument to save an endangered species".
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] *Bloomberg* noted that though the documentary tracks elephant abuse and also refrained from anthropomorphism of elephants, it does not focus on any of the responses from circus owners or enthusiasts.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] Emily Ashby from Common Sense Media mentioned in her review that though the documentary is "eye-opening on a longstanding animal-rights issue", it is one-sided and not advisable viewing for young children.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] A review from *Postmedia News* by Alex Strachan recommended the documentary as an "appropriate viewing on Earth Day" with huge demands for ivory trinkets from China.
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] After the documentary was premiered on HBO, Feld Inc. which is a parent company of Ringling Bros circus expressed that the documentary is a "one-sided hit piece".
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] They mentioned that Amy Schatz contacted them to have "a full range of voices on the subject of elephants" but did not showcase anything saying "the Conservation Center isn't one HBO wants us to cover in the film".
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] They also noted that the documentary has "an anti-circus political agenda".
[src:an-apology-to-elephants/an-apology-to-elephants] Later, HBO issued a statement in response to the allegation from Ringling Bros circus that the documentary "explores a wide range of issues surrounding [but] unfortunately not all can be included in the final film".
